MANDATORY RULES — follow on every request without exception:

1. PIXEL PERFECT
After every generation: ask for screenshot.
During review: deep professional analysis — compare every spacing, font, color, 
component size, border-radius, alignment. Fix ALL differences.
Repeat until 98%+ match. Never skip "minor" differences.
Always list what differs before fixing.

2. NO DESIGN DECISIONS
Never change colors, spacing, or component styles beyond what was requested.
If design shows black button — keep black. Never "improve" design on your own.

3. DESIGN SYSTEM ONLY
Never use window.alert, browser confirms, or default browser UI.
All feedback to user → Toaster, Dialog, Tooltip from components/ui/ only.

4. FILE STRUCTURE
Never put logic in page.tsx — only imports and composition.
Business logic → hooks/use-[name].ts
Shared UI → components/shared/
Page blocks → components/[page-name]/

5. COMPONENTS
Never modify files in components/ui/
Always check if component exists before creating new one.

6. INTERACTIVITY
Always add useState for: radio buttons, checkboxes, tabs, modals, dropdowns.
Never leave interactive elements without state.

7. CONSISTENCY
Before creating any new component, always read existing similar components first.
New components must match existing ones in style, spacing, and structure.

8. FILE STRUCTURE
Never create (app) route groups. Never name files after block slugs.
After any block import — rename to semantic names, move to correct folders, delete demo pages.
One /dashboard, no duplicates.

9. SHADCN STUDIO
After installing shadcn-studio block: move all files to correct folders,
then delete components/shadcn-studio/ completely including empty folders.
Never leave empty folders behind.

10. RESPONSIVE
Every page with sidebar: main content must not be hidden behind it.
Use correct layout: sidebar + flex-1 for content area.
Mobile: sidebar hidden by default with toggle.
Always verify layout before finishing.

11.
ALWAYS start every task by reading .cursorrules file in the project root.
Follow all rules from .cursorrules on every request automatically.
Never wait to be reminded — treat .cursorrules as mandatory context.

12. COLORS
Never hardcode any hex colors. Always use CSS variables from globals.css.
Map any design color to existing tokens. If no token matches → ask before hardcoding.

13. TOKEN MAPPING
globals.css tokens are already synced with Figma design.
When extracting colors from design → always map to CSS variables, never use raw hex.
Mapping: darkest text → text-foreground, secondary text → text-muted-foreground,
primary color → bg-primary text-primary, borders → border-border.
If color from design matches a token → use token, never the hex value.

14. COMPONENT RECOGNITION
Before coding any UI element from a screenshot:
1. Identify all components visible in the design
2. Map each to shadcn/ui component: badge, button, input, select etc.
3. Never use plain HTML when shadcn/ui component exists
Badge is always Badge, never span. Button is always Button, never div.

15. SHADCN FIRST
Before creating ANY component → check if shadcn/ui has it.
If yes → npx shadcn@latest add [name], never create from scratch.
Calendar, DatePicker, Combobox, Select, Dialog — always install, never rewrite.

16. LOCALIZATION
All UI text in Russian by default: labels, placeholders, buttons, errors, empty states.
Date formatting → date-fns with ru locale.
Never use English in UI.

17. SIZING & COLORS
Match component sizes exactly to design.
text-foreground = dark/black text, text-muted-foreground = grey secondary text.
Never use muted-foreground for primary content.
Button size → pick sm/default/lg by visual height in design, never guess larger.

19. DESIGN ACCURACY
When given any screenshot or Figma frame:
1. First analyze all font sizes, spacing, padding, component sizes
2. Map to Tailwind tokens before writing code
3. Never compress spacing or downsize fonts
4. Reproduce layout proportions exactly as shown

20. HOVER STATES
Dropdown menu hover → always rounded-md, never full-width flat.
Never override shadcn/ui default hover styles.
Use design system defaults for all interactive states.

22. DRY PRINCIPLE
Before creating any new modal, form, or page → scan project for similar components.
If differs only in title, button, or data → use mode/type prop in existing component.
Never duplicate structure — one component, different modes via props.
